MAC (Mycobacterium avium complex) prophylaxis study

  • Phase III randomized, double-blind study comparing rifabutin, clarithromycin, and the combination of rifabutin and clarithromycin for prevention of MAC disease in HIV-infected patients with CD4 lymphocyte counts < 100 cells/L.

  • N=1177 patients were accrued over an 8-month period and randomized in equal proportions to the three treatment arms. Patients were followed for a median of 19 months (the study closed in August 1995, prior to the advent of widespread use of protease inhibitors)

Variables of interest:

dthstat : Status

dthtime_1m : time

age

cd4 : CD4 cells/mL

antibiotic: clarithromycin,rifabutin,combination

sex 0: Males, 1:Females

antiret : Antiretroviral experience = Never or unknown=0, Current/previous use=1

# transform to factors: 
mac$antibiotic<-factor(mac$antibiotic,levels = c(1,2,3),labels=c("rifabutin","clarithromycin","combination"))
mac$antiret <- factor(mac$antiret, levels=c(0,1), labels=c("No", "Yes"))

mac$sex <- as.factor(mac$sex)
coxmac_sex <- coxph(Surv(dthtime_1m, dthstat) ~ sex, data = mac)

# Kaplan Meier Curve for Sex
sex.km <- survfit(Surv(dthtime_1m, dthstat) ~ sex, data = mac)
ggsurvplot(sex.km, legend.labs=c("Male", "Female"))

# KM curve plotted with persons in risk

     col = c("darkgreen", "cadetblue"), 
     xlab = "Time to death (months)",
     ylab = "Cum Survival")
# Adding the Number at risk in each time interval

      side = 3, at = sex.km$time[1:30], 
      cex = .4, col = "darkgreen")

log-log survival curves should be parallel which is the case here. So the proportionality assumption holds.

  • observed versus expected plots
#1_Proportionality_observed_vs_predicted
coxmac.s <- coxph(Surv(dthtime_1m, dthstat) ~ antibiotic, data = mac)
plot(survfit(coxph(Surv(dthtime_1m, dthstat) ~ 1,
                   data = mac, 
                   subset = antibiotic == "combination")), 
     conf.int = F, col = "red", lwd = 2, xlim=c(0, 30))
par(new = T)
plot(survfit(coxph(Surv(dthtime_1m, dthstat) ~ 1, 
                   data = mac, 
                   subset = antibiotic == "rifabutin")), 
     conf.int = F, col = "blue", lwd = 2, xlim=c(0, 30))
par(new = T)
plot(survfit(coxph(Surv(dthtime_1m, dthstat) ~ 1, 
                   data = mac, 
                   subset = antibiotic == "clarithromycin")), 
     conf.int = F, col = "violet", lwd = 2, xlim=c(0, 30))
par(new = T)
plot(survfit(coxmac.s, newdata = data.frame(antibiotic = "combination")), 
     col = "red", conf.int = F, xlim=c(0, 30))
par(new = T)
plot(survfit(coxmac.s, newdata = data.frame(antibiotic="rifabutin"), xlim=c(0, 30)), 
     col = "blue", conf.int = F)
par(new = T)

     col = "violet", conf.int = F, xlim=c(0, 30))

Checking linearity

# Create categorical variable from cd4 using quantiles. 
q <- quantile(mac$cd4, c(0, .25, .5, .75, 1))
# the new categorized cd4 is named VarQ
varQ <- cut(mac$cd4, q, include.lowest = T)

We notice that hazard ratios are decreasing with higher quantiles of cd4, so linearity holds.

Interpretation (for the first two: age and sex):

For every year increase in age the hazard of death is increased by 1.026 adjusting for all the other variables in the model. [HR=1.026, 95%CI: (1.016, 1.036), p<0.001].

Being female (sex=1) increases the hazard by a factor of 1.368 adjusting for all the other variables in the model. [HR=1.368, 95%CI: (1.028, 1.822), p=0.031]

Parametric survival models

More information on the distribution used in parametric survival modelling can be found here: https://www.r-bloggers.com/2019/06/parametric-survival-modeling/

# how well is the fitting of exp model? 
# Get the KM estimates and then add the curves fitted by the exponential model
fitKM = survfit( Surv(dthtime_1m, dthstat) ~ sex,data = mac)
plot(fitKM,mark.time = F,main = "Predicted survival for Exponential model VS KM",
     xlab = "Time",ylab = "Survival probability",lty = 1:2,col = c("blue","red"))
pct = seq(0,1,by = 0.001)
lines(predict(fitExp,newdata = data.frame(sex = "0"),type = "quantile",p = pct),1-pct,lty = 3,col = "green")
lines(predict(fitExp,newdata = data.frame(sex = '1'),type = "quantile",p = pct),1-pct,lty = 4,col = "orange")
legend("bottomleft",bty = "n",lty = 1:4,col = c("blue","red","green","orange"),legend = c("KM: Males","KM: Females","EXP: Males","EXP: Females"),ncol = 2)

Exponential model does not fit the data well.

We will fit a Weibull model instead
